# Lesson 2-5 — Solving Equations Involving Absolute Value

Source: (Module 2, Lesson 2-5, Int1_0205_practice.docx)

## Today's Goals

* Solve absolute value equations of the form [ |expression| = constant ] and recognize when no solution exists
* Graph the solution set of an absolute value equation on a number line
* Write absolute value equations that model real-world tolerance, margin-of-error, and range situations
* Translate between number-line graphs and their corresponding absolute value equations

## Vocabulary

* **Absolute value** — The distance of a number from zero on the number line; always nonnegative
* **Tolerance** — An allowable deviation from a specified value in manufacturing or measurement
* **Margin of error** — The range of values above and below a sample statistic in a survey or poll
* **Standard deviation** — A statistical measure of how far data values are from the mean
* **Solution set** — The set of all values that satisfy an equation

## Learn: Solving Absolute Value Equations

An absolute value equation states that the distance between an expression and zero equals a given number.

### Key Concept: Absolute Value Equations

* If [ |A| = p ] and [ p > 0 ], then the equation splits into two cases: [ A = p ] or [ A = -p ] 
* If [ |A| = p ] and [ p < 0 ], there is **no solution** because absolute value is never negative
* If [ |A| = 0 ], there is exactly one solution: [ A = 0 ] 
* After solving, check each solution in the original equation

## Example 1 — Solve and Graph Simple Absolute Value Equations

Solve equations of the form [ |expression| = \text{positive constant} ], then graph the solution set on a number line.

### Step 1: Split into Two Cases

Rewrite the absolute value equation as two separate linear equations.

For [ |x - 3| = 5 ]:
[
x - 3 = 5 \quad \text{or} \quad x - 3 = -5
]

### Step 2: Solve Each Equation

[
x = 8 \quad \text{or} \quad x = -2
]

### Step 3: Graph the Solution Set

Plot both solutions on a number line using closed circles.

Variations include equations with fractions, such as:
[
\left| \frac{3}{4}a - 3 \right| = 9
]

## Example 2 — Identify Equations with No Solution

Determine whether an absolute value equation has solutions before attempting to solve.

### Step 1: Examine the Right-Hand Side

If the constant on the right side is negative, the equation has no solution.

[
|v - 2| = -5 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{no solution}
]
[
|6y - 7| = -1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \text{no solution}
]

### Step 2: Solve When a Solution Exists

When the right-hand side is positive or zero, proceed with the two-case method.

[
|4t - 8| = 20 \quad \Rightarrow \quad 4t - 8 = 20 \; \text{or} \; 4t - 8 = -20
]

## Example 3 — Apply Absolute Value to Real-World Problems

Use absolute value equations to model tolerance, margin of error, and range in everyday contexts.

### Step 1: Identify the Target Value and Allowable Deviation

Determine what quantity represents the center (mean or set point) and what represents the allowed distance from that center.

### Step 2: Write the Absolute Value Equation

For a thermostat set to [ 400^\circ \text{F} ] with a tolerance of [ \pm 15^\circ \text{F} ]:
[
|T - 400| = 15
]

### Step 3: Solve and Interpret

[
T - 400 = 15 \quad \text{or} \quad T - 400 = -15
]
[
T = 415 \quad \text{or} \quad T = 385
]

The maximum temperature is [ 415^\circ \text{F} ] and the minimum is [ 385^\circ \text{F} ].

Contexts include:
* **Polling:** A poll result of [ 38\% ] with [ \pm 5\% ] margin of error
* **Standard deviation:** An ACT mean of [ 20.9 ] with standard deviation [ 5.3 ] 
* **Manufacturing:** A labeled weight of [ 35 ] pounds within [ 8 ] ounces
* **Aviation:** A survey margin of error applied to a population of [ 40 ] million students

## Example 4 — Write Absolute Value Equations from Graphs

Given a number-line graph showing two symmetric points, write the corresponding absolute value equation.

### Step 1: Identify the Center and the Distance

Find the midpoint of the two graphed points — this is the value inside the absolute value expression. Find the distance from the center to either endpoint — this is the constant on the right side.

### Step 2: Construct the Equation

If the graph shows solutions at [ x = -1 ] and [ x = 5 ]:
[
\text{center} = \frac{-1 + 5}{2} = 2, \quad \text{distance} = 3
]
[
|x - 2| = 3
]

Variations include graphs with fractional or negative centers and different distances.

## Mixed Exercises

The mixed exercises integrate all skills from the lesson:

* Solving absolute value equations with variables on either side and fractional coefficients, then graphing the solutions
* Handling equations that require isolating the absolute value first, such as [ 2|h| - 3 = 8 ] or [ 4 - 3|q| = 10 ] 
* Writing absolute value equations from number-line graphs with varied scales and intervals
* Applying absolute value to range, tolerance, and error-bound contexts including temperature control, manufacturing quality, chlorine concentration, and aquarium conditions
